05299nam a22006495i 9780814769492DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t19931993nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147694927 a10.18574/97808147694922doi  a(DE-B1597)550615  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ755.85 .R66 1993 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a306.87431 aRosenzweig, Linda W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Anchor of My Life :bMiddle-Class American Mothers and Daughters, 1880-1920 /cLinda W. Rosenzweig. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[1993] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory of Emotions ;v100tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1. "The Central Problem of Female Experience": Introduction -- t2. "My Girls' Mothers": The Emotionology of Mother-Daughter Relationships, 1880-1920 -- t3. "Cultural Work": Mother-Daughter Relationships in Novels -- t4. "A Girl's Best Friend": Adolescent Daughters and Their Mothers -- t5. "I Am So Glad You Could Go to College": The "New Woman" and Her Mother -- t6. "We Need Each Other": Adult Daughters and Their Mothers -- t7. "The Revolt of the Daughters": Middle-Class English Mothers and Daughters -- t8. "Mother Drove Us in the Studebaker": American Mothers and Daughters after 1920 -- t9. "The Anchor of My Life": Toward a History of Mother-Daughter Relationships -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRelying on women's own words in letters and journals, Rosenzweig refutes the prescriptive literature of the times with its dire predictions of inevitable rifts between Victorian mothers and their daughters, the new women of the twentieth century. Instead Rosenzweig shows us mothers who rejoiced in their daughters' educational successes and, while they did not always comprehend the nature of the changes taking place, were only too happy to see their daughters escape some of their own restrictions and grief. Extremely useful to scholars and teachers of women's history and family history, The Anchor of My Life should also be fascinating to the general public for the accurate window that it provides on these complicated family relationship in our history.-Laurie Crumpacker , Department of History, Simmons College "Drawing on a broad array of historical sources, The Anchor of My Lifechallenges the common assumption that mother-daughter relationships invariably are characterized by tensions and conflicts. This lively and moving book deserves a wide audience."-Emily K. Abel , author of Circles of Care: Work and Identity in Women's Lives The relationship between mothers and daughters has been the subject of much research and study, in such fields as psychoanalysis, sociology, and women's studies. But rarely has the history and evolution of this relationship been examined. In The Anchor of My Life, Linda W. Rosenzweig draws on a wide range of primary sources--letters, diaries, autobiographies, prescriptive advice or self-help literature, and fiction-to reveal the historical nuances of this pivotal relationship. Rosenzweig's distinctive approach focuses on the interaction between mothers and daughters of the American middle class at the turn of the century, revealing that mothers and daughters managed to sustain close, nurturing relationships in an era marked by a major female generation gap in terms of aspirations and opportunities. Illustrated with photographs and portraits of the time, The Anchor of My Life provocatively challenges the facile, late twentieth-century assumption that the mother-daughter relationship is necessarily defined by hostility, guilt, and antagonism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aMiddle cla